The paper deals with personalized search on LinkedIn, which involves natural language processing and machine learning techniques to extract searcher intents from their profile data and recent activities. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Information Retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category, which deals with techniques for searching and retrieving information from large datasets. Additionally, the paper mentions the use of slideshows, which could indicate a focus on multimedia information retrieval (cs.MM). 

The paper also mentions the use of natural language processing techniques, which could suggest a focus on Computational Linguistics (cs.CL) sub-category. Furthermore, the paper mentions the use of A/B testing to evaluate the effectiveness of the approach, which could indicate a focus on Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category. 

The paper also deals with personalization of search results, which could suggest a focus on Cybersecurity (cs.CY) sub-category, which deals with techniques for protecting personal information and data. Finally, the paper mentions the use of member engagement as a metric for evaluating the effectiveness of the approach, which could indicate a focus on Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) sub-category.
